			<h3 id="comments-title">6 Responses to <em>Why using Maven for Clojure builds is a&nbsp;no-brainer</em></h3>


			<ol class="commentlist">
					<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-105">
		<div id="comment-105">
		<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/7c22f533ef0362294163c00e54cee3bc?s=40&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />			<cite class="fn">gdjsky01</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://cemerick.com/2010/03/25/why-using-maven-for-clojure-builds-is-a-no-brainer/#comment-105">
			March 25, 2010 at 9:24 am</a>		</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

		<div class="comment-body"><p>Maven for any project bigger than a source file quickly becomes a beast you will never tame. I have mega-projects in maven and I cringe and take downers everytime I have to modify a POM. As seen on twitter: &#8220;The difference between ant and maven is the author of ant has apologized.&#8221; Or as I have said, Maven is Native American for dependency hell. However I should mention, the plugin is a very fast way to get a clojure build environment running. Far far faster than anything else I have tried in emacs. With it, you can get a REPL up and running in no time and use swank-connect to plug emacs into it. But as a long term, large project tool, it&#8217;s like Rube Goldberg on speed.</p>
</div>

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/03/25/why-using-maven-for-clojure-builds-is-a-no-brainer/?replytocom=105#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-105", "105", "respond", "323")'>Reply</a>		</div><!-- .reply -->
