		<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/7c22f533ef0362294163c00e54cee3bc?s=40&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />			<cite class="fn">gdjsky01</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://cemerick.com/2010/03/25/why-using-maven-for-clojure-builds-is-a-no-brainer/#comment-108">
			March 25, 2010 at 9:26 am</a>		</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

		<div class="comment-body"><p>Not hyperbole. Experience. But please, feel free to make the same (IMO) mistake. Wait till you need to do something slightly outside simple &#8216;examples&#8217;. &#8220;&#8230; don&#8217;t confuse inherent for incidental complexity.&#8221; Rich Hickey right?? Remember I am trying Clojure and fp to adopt that philosophy as best I can &#8211; undoing 25 years of C/C++/Java. I am listening (and learning.) I think it&#8217;ll make me a better engineer. However starting with a tools programmed in data interchange format (XML) is exactly the opposite of what you just quoted. Maven starts with the wrong solution and makes it work. So there we agree to disagree. YMMV. Still I enjoy your writing. People can an will disagree on the details. And yes, the plugin is a GREAT way to get going fast. And used just for that, is a &#8216;no-brainer&#8217;.</p>
</div>

